'''''Rural Heritage''''' is a bimonthly [[magazine]] published for America’s past and present enthusiasts of [[working animal|animal power]]. [[File:Rural Heritage logo.jpg|thumb|Rural Heritage logo]]
==History and profile== First published in 1976,<ref name="mbbos">{{cite book|author=Mary Burzlaff Bostic|title=2016 Artist's & Graphic Designer's Market|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bvHJCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT633|accessdate=December 13, 2015|date=October 19, 2015|publisher=F+W Media|isbn=978-1-4403-4263-9|page=633}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ruralheritage.com/business_office/index.htm|title=Rural Heritage Business Office|accessdate=January 24, 2011}}</ref> the magazine was named as ''the Evener''.<ref name=abe>{{cite web|title=12 issues Rural Heritage Magazine (formally The Evener)|url=http://www.abebooks.com/issues-Rural-Heritage-Magazine-formally-Evener/5571192245/bd|publisher=Abe Books|accessdate=13 December 2015}}</ref> It serves small farmers and loggers who use [[draft horse]]s, [[mule]]s, and [[oxen]] in their business. The former headquarters was in [[Knoxville, Tennessee]].<ref name=abe/> The headquarters of the magazine is in [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]].<ref name=mbbos/><ref>{{cite web|title=Editorial Guidelines|url=https://www.ruralheritage.com/new_rh_website/advertise/editorial_guidelines.shtml|work=Rural Heritage|accessdate=December 13, 2015}}</ref> It is self-published on a small Iowa farm, and distributes its issues mainly through direct mailing. Some farm and feed stores such as [[Tractor Supply]] also carry the magazine. ''Rural Heritage'' is currently edited by Joe Mischka.<ref name=mbbos/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mondotimes.com/2/topics/5/sports/3/5611|title=MondoTimes|accessdate=January 24, 2011}}</ref> Previously, the magazine was edited by Gail Damerow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motherearthnews.com/Sustainable-Farming/2002-06-01/Want-Milk-Get-Goats.aspx|title=Want Milk? Get Goats|accessdate=September 27, 2011}}</ref>
