{{Infobox ancient site |name = Wadi Yaroun |native_name = |alternate_name = Wadi Yaroun |image = |alt = |caption = |map_type = Lebanon |map_alt = |map_size = 200 |location = south of [[Ain Ebel]], [[Lebanon]] |region = [[Nabatieh Governorate]] |coordinates = {{coord|33.08778|35.39667|display=inline}} |type = |part_of = |length = |width = |area = |height = |builder = |material = |built = |abandoned = |epochs = [[Heavy Neolithic]], [[Neolithic]] |cultures = [[Qaraoun culture]] |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = |archaeologists = [[Paul Bovier-Lapierre]], [[Henri Fleisch]] |condition = |ownership = |management = |public_access = Yes |website = |notes = }} [[File:Heavyneolithicpick.jpg|right|250px|thumb|Heavy Neolithic pick of the Qaraoun culture - Double ended pick, triangular section with narrowing, jagged edges at both ends. Found at [[Mtaileb I]].]] '''Wadi Yaroun''', '''Wadi Yarun''', '''Wadi Jarun''', '''Wadi Hanine''', '''Jarun''' or '''Jareon''' is a [[wadi]] located south of [[Ain Ebel]] in the [[Bint Jbeil District]] of [[Nabatieh Governorate]] in [[Lebanon]].<ref name="Crawford1927">{{cite book|author=Osbert Guy Stanhope Crawford|title=Antiquity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u443AAAAMAAJ|accessdate=5 September 2012|year=1927|publisher=Antiquity Publications}}</ref> After it reaches [[Yaroun]] it is called the '''Wadi Nahle''' or '''Wadi Nalesh''' and after reaching [[Debel, Lebanon|Debel]] it is called the '''Wadi Ayun et Tannour'''.<ref name="CopelandWescombe1966">{{cite book|author1=L. Copeland|author2=P. Wescombe|title=Inventory of Stone-Age Sites in Lebanon: North, South and East-Central Lebanon, p. 89|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qhPRQwAACAAJ|accessdate=3 March 2011|year=1966|publisher=Impr. Catholique}}</ref><ref name="Moore">{{cite book|last=Moore|first=A.M.T.|title=The Neolithic of the Levant|publisher=Oxford University, Unpublished Ph.D. Thesis|year=1978|pages=428–433|url=http://ancientneareast.tripod.com/178.html}}</ref>
A [[Heavy Neolithic]] archaeological site of the [[Qaraoun culture]] was discovered by [[Paul Bovier-Lapierre]] west north west of Yaroun and south of Ain Ebel;<ref>Bovier-Lapierre, Paul., Stations préhistoriques du Beled Becharra (The Galilée), La Géographie, vol. 17, p. 77, 1908.</ref> [[Lorraine Copeland]] remarked that ''"the surface of this valley is literally covered in (worked [[flint]]) flakes"''. Bovier-Lapierre recovered several unpolished and polished axes with one exceptional elongated piece. All sorts of blades, scrapers, discs and other tools were found on the site and were stored with the [[Saint Joseph University]] (now the [[Museum of Lebanese Prehistory]]). [[Henri Fleisch]] determined the collection also included some later [[Neolithic]] pieces.<ref name="CopelandWescombe1966"/>
